value:
@lumodon,
I want to work with you because:
You understand the arbitrary concepts laid out in code examples on websites almost no matter how little code exists there.

I would want to work with you more if:
You wouldn't doubt yourself or beat yourself up so much. It IS ok to make mistakes and/or not know what you don't know. It's not a fault to not know, admitting it is even more powerful.

Also, knowing vocabulary/terminology about the topic at hand helps to eliminate confusion during conversation.

subject: Melody
value: I want to work with you because you are clearly a very good developer and I also can see the way you visualize problems is very sophisticated. It was difficult to work with you this week because of our communication. There was something about pairing that got in the way of our flow and took time away from us accomplishing tasks. It was difficult to see your process in planning and although I know you had the capability to accomplish our tasks I felt it was difficult for me to see you wanting to work within our teams established norms for contributing. For example, staying within the scope of our tickets, challenging the way we contribute. I think criticism is healthy, but at some point we need to balance getting the project done. I also challenge you to self-asses to accurately give your team members an idea of how long you think it would take you to complete tasks. For example, you said you thought client and server validation would be done by Monday. If it isn't, and it ended up being a more difficult problem, or because of the existing code base...that is fine. I just wish you had been more upfront and acknowledge that so you and your team member could be on the same page.
